Interestingly, different parameters affected cell shape to a different extent (Fig. 6). Thus, changing the value of the PW parameter from 1 to 2 to 4 resulted in visually distinct cells (Figs. 6a, S5a) and large quantitative differences between the cell shapes (Fig. 6b). Changing the value of NW from 1 to 2 to 4 resulted in a similarly large quantitative difference (Fig. 6d), but the cells’ 3D surface reconstructions were hard to distinguish visually (Fig. 6c). Only looking at the cells’ maximum projections revealed that – indeed – lower NW values resulted in a more structured cell surface (Fig. S5b). For the DW parameter, both 3D surfaces and maximum projections were similar (Figs. 6e, S5c) for different parameter values (2, 4, and 6), and no significant differences in cell shape could be identified by the static classifier (Fig. 6f). In contrast, when shape dynamics was included, the classifier accuracy was significantly higher than random, indicating that the visually similar cells might evolve their shape in different ways. Interestingly, different value ranges of the FR parameter had different effects on the cell shape, even though the parameter values were equally spaced. Thus, cell shape did not change when the value of FR increased from 0 to 0.3, which was both observed visually (Figs. 6g, S5d) and reflected by the close-to-random classifier accuracy (Fig. 6h). In contrast, cell shape for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
